S1: 55 year old male with a history of diabetes and hypertension complains of 1 hour of substernal chest pain described as a heaviness, associated with dyspnea and diaphoresis. no nausea, vomiting fever or chills. pain is not pleuritic. no lower extremity dvt symptoms and no PE risk factors. On exam, heart rate- 105, blood pressure - 100/80, pulse ox 98% on rooom air, mild distress and diaphoretic, alert and oriented. lungs clear, abdomen nontender and no edema, no jvd. suspect acute coronary syndrome.

S2: ekg shows lateral twave inversions. troponin- 2.5.

S3: working diagnosis, NSTEMI. patient was given 1 liter bolus of ns, 325mg of ASA, 5mg lopressor, 1mg dilaudid, heparin drip, and his symptoms have improved and vitals normalized. patient transferred to higher level of care, discussed with cardiologist on call.